Multiply that by 364*363*362*...*340*339*338 (choosing the unique birthdays of the rest)
Choose the 4 person subset in 30!/(4!*26!) ways, where n! means n*(n-1)*(n-2)*...*3*2*1, and choose their shared bday in 365 ways.
All possible birthdate assignments: 365^30 (for each person, choose any day). This will be the denominator.
Simplifying assumptions: ignoring leap day; of the remaining 26, all birthdays are unique

The probability that I throw a dart and hit, say, between 0.0 and 0.1, is 10%. That should seem relatively obvious.

the bullet, given time, has 0% probability of being anywhere but the bottom. ergodic hypothesis NOT satisfied.
but, given enough time, there's mixing. so any given molecule is equally likely to be in any part of the tank. ergodic hypothesis satisfied!
let's dump some chemicals into our bullet tank. in the short term, there's a swirly chaotic cloud of molecules clumped in one region
we have left my area of expertise, but i think the ergodic hypothesis can be made into metaphor as follows:
(i SAID the subsets were small!)
metaphor: "We want to study The Things In The Universe, but that's hard. so i'll start by studying ducks, and you start by studying squid."
analogously: the ergodic hypothesis is a restriction to a different tiny subset of all functions, and gives a different toolkit to use
that toolkit is awesome! but works only on the very small set of functions we've limited ourselves to by assuming those hypotheses
the continuity and differentiability hypotheses are the assumptions that say "You may now safely use the calculus toolkit".
in mathspeak, we are assuming that the function is continuous and differentiable; i.e., our bullet is well-behaved enough to do calculus on
for our bullet, we assumed no teleporting, no instantaneous right-angle turns or drops to absolute zero as it travels its state space.
Rules for Radicals (Alinsky) is amazing so far. a study in divorcing revolution-as-change (ie tactics) from revolution-as-ideology #books
i'll let that simmer through breakfast and see if i can figure out exactly what the ergodic assumption MEANS :)
assuming something is "ergodic" is a similar cheat for making the problem "easy" *cough* and b/c we want to study a particular phenomenon.
but they're much easier to deal with and all sorts if things behave continuously, so it's a useful and honorable cheat to study this subset.
mathematicians say that the function telling us about the bullet is "continuous". continuous functions are a tiny subset of all functions
but we cheat in line with reality. e.g.,, we assume that over tiny periods of time, any measurement of the bullet changes just a little
it would be great if we had a complete theory of how to solve all dynamical system problems, but they're crazy hard. so, we cheat.
